issue.body:
When loading JSON-LD, the blank node's ID is taken from the jsonld-java library. The library uses a counter to generate blank node ID's. So the blank nodes returned by jsonld-java are same for different files - it. they are "unique" just in the scope of a file . The rdf4j however uses these names to identify the blank nodes even between files.

The problem with this situation can be illustrated on a simple example:
File ```in1.jsonld``` : ``` { "http://localhost/ontology/filePredicate": "in1.jsonld" } ```
File ```in2.jsonld``` : ``` { "http://localhost/ontology/filePredicate": "in2.jsonld" } ```
The Java code: 
```    
public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Model model = new LinkedHashModel();
        try (InputStream stream = new FileInputStream("in1.jsonld")) {
            model.addAll(Rio.parse(stream, "http://localhost/base", RDFFormat.JSONLD));
        }
        try (InputStream stream = new FileInputStream("in2.jsonld")) {
            model.addAll(Rio.parse(stream, "http://localhost/base", RDFFormat.JSONLD));
        }
        try (OutputStream stream = new FileOutputStream("rdf4j.ttl")) {
            Rio.write(model, stream, RDFFormat.TURTLE);
        }
    }
```
Content of the output file (```rdf4j.ttl```): 
``` 
_:b0 <http://localhost/ontology/filePredicate> "in1.jsonld" , "in2.jsonld" . 
```
while it should be 
```
_:b0 <http://localhost/ontology/filePredicate> "in1.jsonld" .
_:b1 <http://localhost/ontology/filePredicate>  "in2.jsonld" .
```
We would get the same result with Repository, but the code for Model is shorter. 

I also tested similar code with Jena, where I got the expected result.

This behaviour is also not compatible with other loaders. For example, if I load two Turtle files, with two blank nodes of the same identifiers, I should got different blank nodes.  This works as Turtle loader give unique IDs to blank nodes even in different files. However as the jsonld-java "reuse" the identifiers, this does not hold for the JSON-LD.

One solution is to use a wrap for the RdfHandler and modify the blank node's ID (for example add a file based prefix).

The used version of rdf4j is 2.2
